{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_grenada_ver01/data/sn99062034/00279523064/1910091301/1174.xml":{"full_text":"POWDER\nAbsolutely Pure\nThe only baking powder\nmade from Royal Grape\nCream of Tartar\nNo Alum, No Lime Phosphate\nhas cueist\nOF EHMOiS\nComptroller Murray Would\nBar Certain Men.\nREADY TO FlRNISa NAMES\nTells State Bank Examiners That the\nList in His Office Will Be Given\nThem for Use Should Any of the\n\"Undesirables'1 Attempt to Organize\nState Institutions \u2014Has Refused\nMany Applications Since Taking\nOffice.\nWashington, S]t. 13.\u2014The Na\ntional Association of Supervisors of\nState Banks begun a three days' con\nvention in Washington. The exam\niners gathered at the treasury build\ning and were addressed by Lawrence\nO Murray, comptroller of the cur\nrency.\nMr. Murray proposed to the state\nsupervisors a working co-operation\nwith the national examiners. He de\nclared he had in his office a list of\nmen who, as officers of the national\nbanks, had proved incompetent and\nhad been removed from office and\nsaid that if any of them should make\napplication to order state banks their\nnames would he furnished to the state\nbanking authorities. In turn he pro\nposed that the state supervisors fur\nnish to the national system the names\nof men who had been driven out ot\nthe state bankB.\nDuring the last eighteen months the\ncomptroller said he had refused 10s\napplications to form national banks\nbecause the men behind them had\nbeen found incompetent or dishonest\nthat there was not enough business\nto make the proposed institutions\nprofitable or that the applicants were\nspeculators or men without standing\nin their communities.\nTHREE MEN UNDER ARREST\nAre Charged With Recent Incendiary\nFires at New Duluth.\nDuluth, Sept. 13 \u2014The sixth incen\ndiary fire in New Duluth completely\ndestroyed the finishing room and ware\nhouse of the Thompson Furniture\ncompany and caused a loss estimated\nat $30,000, about half covered by in\nsurance.\nThree men. said to have been seen\nrunning away from the scene, were\narrested on suspicion of having started\nthe conflagration and were taken to\npolice headquarters for examination.\nThe fire was the most disastrous yet\nreported.\nLast week the plant of the W. H.\nRieckhoff bo* factory was burned,\nwith a loss of $20,000, partly insured\nPreviously the company suffered from\ntwo fires, causing a combined loss of\nabout $50,000. The Thompson Furni\ntune company had a small blaze and\nthe New Duluth Lumber company had\na loss of $2,000 a short time ago. One\nof these fires undoubtedly was of In\ncendiary origin.\nBULLION STOLEN FROM SHIP\nLead Substituted for Gold Being\nBrought From Alaska.\n8eattle, Sept. 13.\u2014Gold bullion val\nued at $57,\"00, part of a consignment\nof $170,000 from the Washington\nAlaska bank of Fairbanks to the Dex\nter-Horton National bank of Seattle,\non the steamship Humboldt, was\nstolen in transit, l^sad was substi\ntuted in the strong box that contained\nit. The stolen gold weighed 250\npounds.\nThe gold was insured against lots\nV\u201e TK* \u00abM\u00bbU\niv*roIUUI*\nFREIGHT RATES\nAREJOO LOW\nPennsylvania Official Before\nCommerce Commission,\nSAYS ACTION\nWAS\nDELAYED\nTariffs Should Have Been Increased\nIn 1908, He Asserts, but Adjustment\nWas Put Off Because of Business\nDepression\u2014Matter Now imperative\nBecause of Recent Advances in\nWages.\nNew York, Sept. 13.\u2014John B.\nThayer, third vice president of the\nPennsylvania railroad, told the inter\nstate commerce commission, which is\ninquiring into the question of in\ncreased freight tariffs by the Eastern\nroads, that the rates between the East\nand West have for years been too low\nand that the tariffs should have been\njaised in 1908. The adjustment, how\never, was delayed until the business\ndepression had passed, the witness\nsaid.\n\"The matter of advancing rates\ncame to a head wtth the recent wage\ndemands,\" said Mr. Thayer. \"It is\nnot an extraordinary and unprecedent\ned advance in rates, but is In line with\nour established practice for two\nyears.\"\nMr. Thayer said that passenger\nrates were not compensatory for the\nservice rendered, but that the public,\nthrough its legislatures, would not\nstand for an advance in their passen\nger fares. He said that the rates on\nthrough traffic had been too low in\ncomparison with local rates.\nConsidering the matter of freight\ntariffs Mr. Thayer said:\nQuestion of Freight Tariffs.\n\"A car of first class freight from\nNqw York or Boston, 1.100 miles to\nChicago, would, at high speed, bring\njust $75. A car of steel from Pitts\nburg to New York, less than half the\ndistance, loaded and unloaded tor us,\nbrings twice the revenue.\n\"On everything from Boston to Chi\ncago we only get 55 cents a hundred\nand have to pay the New Haven rail\nroad 20 per cent of It for bringing it\nto Jersey City.\"\nMr. Thayer said In conclusion:\n\"While the estimated increase of\nthis advance on lines east of Pittsburg\nis $3,o00,000, which is a large sum, it\nmust be remembered as far as the\nPennsylvania railroad is concerned\nthat we deal with very large and huge\nfigures and, after all, that the amount\nonly represents 2.3 per cent of our\ngross earnings from freight traffic and\n1.6 per cent of our total gross earn\nings from all sources, so that it is not\na large standard advance, in our opin\nion, but a mere readjustment of rates\nto bring us a portion of the revenues\nwe must have in order to meet de\nmands made upon us.\"\nTO RESUME RATE HEARINGS\nCommerce Commission Will Take Up\nCases in the Weet\nWashington, Sept. 13.\u2014Judge Mar\ntin A. Knapp, chairman of the inter\nstate commerce commission, just re\nturned from his vacation trip, gave\nassurance that the supplemental tes\ntimony In the freight rate cases, of\nboth the East and West, would be\nheard by members of the commission\nIt is likely that Commissioner Proutv\nwill sit in the Western case at Chi\ncago on the resumption of the hearing\non the 19th inst. If his health shall\npermit Commissioner Clark also may\nbe on the bench with Mr. Prouty.\nREASON FOR ACT UNKNOWN\nHome Of Mine Official at Ctiomet,\nMich., Dynamited.\nCalumet, Mich., Sept. 13.\u2014An unsuc\ncessful attempt was made to kill\nFrank Phillips, master mechanic of\nthe Kearsarge mine, and his family. A\nstick of dynamite was set off, partiallj\nwrecking the dwelling and smashing\ndishes and other contents. Two sus\npects have been arrested. The cause\nof the deed is unknown.\nSTEAMER GROUNDS NEAR S00\nForward Tanks Are Punctured and\nVessel Is Beached.\nSault Ste Marie, Mich Sept. 13.\nThe steamer Pontiac, upbound, struck\nthe middle ground at the mouth of St\nMary's river. The forward tanks were\npunctured and rapidly filled. The ves\nsel was beached on (laffneys point to\navoid sinking. The crew is safe.\nAbruzzi Engagement Denied.\nRome, Sept. 13.\u2014A semi-official com\nmunication issued by an Italian\nagency declares that the reports print\ned in Italy and abroad of the ap\nproaching marriage of the Duke of the\nAbruzzi and Miss Katherlne Elkins\nabsolute'v\nACTRESSES TO QUIT STAGE.\nBillie Burke and Pauline\nChase, Who Will Wed Soon.\nSLAYER AND ONE VICTIM DEAD\nJealouey Cause of Triple 8hootlng at\nRedfield, S. D.\nRed field, S. D., Sept. 13.\u2014Crazed by\njealousy H. V. Harveson, a drug clerk\nof this city, shot and killed Dale\nKiser, a prominent young lady, seri\nously wounded Dr. F. K. Clinite, a\ndentist, and then killed himself. The\nshooting occurred at the young lady's\nhome.\nDr. Clinite had been calling upon\nher and just as he was leaving was\nmet at the door by Harveson, who\nshot him twice through the right lung\nand once through the arm after\nClinite had fallen. He then shot the\ngirl above the heart, killing her al\nmost instantly. Clinite and Miss Kiser\nfell in the hallway of the house and\nHarveson stepped out on the porch\nand shot himself through the head.\nNEW YORK WORLD\nATTACSCSROOSEVELT\nDemands to Know How Much\nTrusts Save Him in 1904.\nNew York, Sept. 13.\u2014Quoting at\nlength from the speech of Colonel\nRoosevelt at Osawatomie, Kan., Aug\n31, the World editorially demands that\nthe colonel make public the ,receipts\nand expenditures of the national cam\npaign of 1904. It says:\n\"In the campaign of 1904 the World\nsubmitted to you ten questions that\nwent to the very heart of your stew\nardship. Lest you have forgotten\nthem we reprint them.\n\"How much has the beef trust, the\npaper trust, the coal trust, the sugar\ntrust, the oil trust, the tobacco trust,\nthe steel trust, the insurance trust,\nthe national banks and the six great\nrailroad trusts contributed to Mr. Cor\ntelyou?\n\"Your 1904 campaign fund has nev\ner been publicly accounted for except\nas fragmentary facts have come to\nlight through public investigations\nand otherwise. Mr. Cortelyou has nev\ner publicly accounted for one singl\npenny of the millions that he collected\nto elect you president. You are the\nman who sealed his lips and kept\nthem sealed for six years.\n\"We know the life insurance com\npanies contributed $150,000 of their\npolicyholders' funds that Harrlman\nraised a corruption fund of $260,000\nto which he personally contributed\n$,'.0,000 that Standard Oil contributed\n$100,000 and the beef trust and othei\ncorporations contributed.\n\"We know that while you after\nwards attacked the beef trust, you\nnever personally proceeded against\nthe officers and directors, although the\nSherman law, as Justice Holmes onc\ntold you, is 'a criminal statute.' We\nknow that while you afterward public\nly attacked the Standard Oil company\nyou never proceeded against its offi\ncers personally.\"\nThe editorial refers specifically in\nsimilar terms to the failure to crim\ninally prosecute Harriman and officers\nof the sugar trust or to enjoin the ab\nsorption of the Tennessee Coal and\nIron company by the sUel trust\nMADISON, SOUTH DAKOTA, TIKSOAV, SEPTEMKKR 13, 191\u00a9\nFOUGHT FLAKES\nFOR TWO WEEKS\nOcean Liner Reaches Havre\nWith Fire\nin\nHold.\nCREW NEARLY EXHAUSTED\nHad Battle With the Blaze From the\nMoment of Discovery Until the Ves\nsel Arrived at Her Destination\u2014City\nFiremen Are Flooding the Steamer\nin the Hops of tevinfl Part of th#!\nCargo.\nHavre, Sept. 13.\u2014The FreHvh freight\nand passenger steamer California ar\nlived from New York with a fire\nwhich had been fought for twelve days\nstill burning in her hold. The crew\nwas nearly exhausted and called on\nthe city firemen to finish the job. The\nlatter proceeded to flood the craft and\nhope to save part of the cargo.\nThe California h|d sixteen passen\ngers, none of whom was hurt.\nThe steamer, which carries only sec\nond class passengers, and not many of\nthem, is owned by \"the Compagnie Gen\nerate Trans-Atlantique. She sailed\nfrom New York for Havre on Aug. 27\nwith a load of merchandise. On Sept.\n1 a puff of smoke rose from one of the\nhatchways and warned the master of\ntrouble below. An investigation un\ncovered a blaze that had been working\nits way into the cargo untj.1 it got a\nstart that was too much for the crew\nFrom the moment of discovery until\nthe California drew into the harbor\nher sailors had little rest. They were\nsuccessful, however, in keeping the\nnames below deck.\nBRIQANDS HOLD UP STEAMER\nChinese Bandits Kill Owner* of Ves\nsel and Rob Passengers.\nHarbin, Manchuria, Sept. 13\u2014A\nband of brigands, disguised as passon\ngers, held up a Russian steamer sou'ti\nof this port and, after a fight, over\ncame the crew and robbed the passen\ngers. In attempting to defend tin\n-i\nvessel the owners, two Russians, were\nkilled and many of the Chinese\nv w\nand Chinese passengers were wound\ned.\nWhen the pirates were In control of\nthe situation they bound the passen\ngers, the crew, a Russian sailor an\ntwo Russian women and took the val\nuables of the captives at their leisure\nA boatload of hunters who happened\nto be in the vicinity gave the alarm\nand a Russian gunboat was sent in\npursuit of the outlaws,\nTO CONNECT WITH HILL LINES\nHuge Canadian Railroad Proposition\nComes to Light.\nEdmonton, Alta. Sept. II.\u2014A huge\nrailway proposition backed by exten\nsive New York capital for the con\nstruction of a line of railway which\nwill traverse the entire length oi Al\nberta from the international boundary\nto Peace River landing, a distance of\nmore than 700 miles, and which will\nconnect with the Hill system in Mon\ntana, was laid before Premier Sifton\nby representatives of New York capi\ntalists, railway builders and coal men,\nwho have already organized a com\npany to build the line and who have\ncompleted the surveys for the first\n100 miles. Premier Sifton affixed his\nsignature to the plans for the first 100\nmiles of the road.\nYEGGMEN WRECK THE BANK\nWatchman at Henry, S. D., Is Bound\nand Gagged by Robbers.\nWatertown, S. D., Sept. 13.\u2014Four\nmen wrecked the State bank of Henry\nin an attempt to blow the safe. After\nbinding and gagging the night watch\nman the robbers demolished the side\nof the vault with tools stolen frtfm a\nsection house. Five nitroglycerin\nblasts failed to open the safe. The\nmen stole a team and a buggy with\nwhich to get out of town.\nRobbers Hold Up Rich Autoists.\nPoughkeepsie, N. Y., Sept. 13.\u2014\nMasked bandits, working with a free\ndom of manner that would have done\nJesse James and his band proud, held\nup three wealthy Poughkeepsie resi\ndents at the point of revolvers and\nstripped them of much jewelry, $1!)0\nin cash and valuable papers. One\nfired two shots at one of the autoists\nwho resisted beinfi sear died, narrowly\nmissing him.\nChicago's Oldest Lawyer Dead.\nChicago, Sept. 13.-George Laban\nPaddock, lawyer and financier, seven\nty-seven years old, is de.id at. his\nhome here. In number of years of\nservice Mr. Paddock was probably the\noldest lawyer in the city, having spent\nfifty-one years at his profession.\n11\nen\nUjv\nDuluth, Sept. 13.\u2014The work of con\nstruction of the extension of the Cana\ndian Northern road front Virginia to\nDuluth, a distance of about seventy\nfive miles, is now in full swing, and\nmore than 2,000 men are employed\nThe road is graded and ready for bal\nlasting between Virginia and the St\nTx)uis river Work across the mus\nkeag sections of the right of way has\nbeen unusually easy because of the\nfact that it has been a dry season\nDefinite plana for the yards, which are\nto occupy tne space west of the Duluth\nBelt Line road in West Duluth and\nthe park, have not yet been received.\nHow one man\nfooled his wife\nShe had\n1\ni o u u using\nher \"favorite\"\na k i n n v e\nWouldn't till::::\ncf\ntry* Hfij favohitJ]\ning anything else, bo*\ncause \"mother alwaya\nused it,\" or some similar\n\\cuae. Hubby said she\nwas\nprejudiced. He figured if\nCalumet, tho new bahiilg\npowder, selling r.t a moder\nate price, could be so successful, there must be some good in it. So he took a hand, and\nbought a can of Calumet, emptied the can containing her \"favorite\" baking powder and\nfilled it with Calumet.\nThat evening, uncanpcctlng the trick, Wifey prepared and served tome ol her famous biscuit\u2014\npiping hot, temptingly browned and puffed up to airy lightness, they were even more deliciomi\nthan usual. Hubhy, after considerable dilficultv, succeeded in convincing her that the basil\nof the improvement wan Calumet Baking powder. And so an i.Wt\nlasting friend for Calurnct w&j'made. JF\nThis truthful little iacident simply proves that the hooaewife is of times prejudiced\nagainst all hakinrr povdors except the one sho has been using for years. She\nimagines that no other kind can possibly be as good. This is a mistaken impression.\nA trial of Calumet wili prove tl.r.t it is purer, mon- reliable it has a greater leavening\npower than any other baking pawdor made. And it is moderate in price.\nYour Grocer Will Guarantee It Ask Him for\nCALUMET\nBAKING POWDER\nRfcpn w! Award World's Pure\nKoJ .poaition, Chicago, 1907\nIn Order to Quickly Introduce\nARDEE FLOUR\nIn Madison, we are offering a special bargain on a\n42-PIECE DINNER SET\nYour grocer will give you full particulars.\nARDEE is a SPECIAL PATENT. Milled under our\nown distinctive process. All wheat is thoroughly\nwashed in Pure Artesian Well Water before grind*\ning.\nWe Guarntee ARDEE to be the Cleanest, Purest\nand Best Flour on the Market, and to Produce\nMore and Better Bread to the Sack or Your Groc\ner Will Refund Your Money.\nIf you appreciate purity, cleanliness and quality\nARDEE FLOUR\nFor Sale By All Grocers\n\"I* Life Worth Saving?\"\nMrs*. Mollis McKancy, Prentiss, Miss.,\nwrites that she had a severe case of kid\nney trouble, and that four bottles of\nFoley Kidney lieinedy oured her Bound\nand well. She clones her letter by say\ning, i'I heartily recommend Foley's Kid\nney Remedy to any sufferer of kidney\ndisease. It saved my life. Sold by all\ndruggists\nFoley's Kidney remedy will cure any\ncase of kidney and bladder trouble not\nbeyond the reach of medicine. No med\nicine can do more Sold by all druggist\nDeWitt's Kidney and Bladder FiHa\nFOR BACKACHE\nJm\ns\ni\n'Folev Kidney Pills Have Cured Me*\nThe above is a quotation from a letter\nwritten by M. Winkler, EvansvilMv\nInd. \"I contracted a severe case of kid\nney trouble. My back gave out and\npained me. I seemed to have lost al)\nstrength and ambition was bothered\nwith dizzy spells, my head would swim\nand specks float before my eyes. I took\nFoley s Kidney Pills regularly and am\nnow perfectly well and feel like a new\nman. Foley Kidney Pills have cured\nSM.\" Sold by all druggHt*\n.w/*","height":"24702","width":"19692"}}
